@zcbenz I did have main.js in the sub-directory `./app` that I was pointing it to. I think the problem was the way node.js require works is it pulled in my current working directory `./app` when it did a `require('app')` instead of using the atom-shell `app` module.

I renamed my "app" subdirectory to "hello-app" and created a `./build` directory to hold the Gruntfile and downloaded atom-shell versions (I think the atom project does something like this) to avoid confusion and now it seems to work fine:

`./build/atom-shell/Atom.app/Contents/MacOS/Atom ./hello-app`

It seems I ran into the same issue; the error I received for

``` javascript
var app = require('app');
var BrowserWindow = require('browser-window');

app.on('window-all-closed', function() {
  if (process.platform != 'darwin') app.quit();
});

app.on('ready', function() {
  mainWindow = new BrowserWindow({width: 800, height: 600});
  mainWindow.loadUrl('file://' + __dirname + '/index.html');

  mainWindow.on('closed', function() {
    mainWindow = null;
  });
});
```

was `Object has no method "on"` on line 4. Renaming my folder from `app` to something else (I used `webapp`) fixed the problem.
